Let ${\cal A}$ be a C$^*$-algebra and let $({\frak H}_1, \pi_1)$ and $({\frak H}_2, \pi_2)$ be nondegenerate representations of ${\cal A}$.
The representations $\pi_1$ and $\pi_2$ is quasi-equivalent, if there exists an isomorphism $\gamma : \pi_1({\cal A})^{\prime\prime} \mapsto \pi_2({\cal A})^{\prime\prime}$ such that $\gamma(\pi_1(A)) = \pi_2(A)$ for all $A \in {\cal A}$ (see also \cite[Definition 2.4.25]{BratteliRobinsonII} and \cite[Theorem2.4.26]{BratteliRobinsonII}).
If a subrepresentation of $\pi_1$ is quasi-equivalent to $\pi_2$, then $\pi_1$ is quasi-contain $\pi_2$.
